            <p>by Mikayla Bouchard<br />May 2015</p>
            
            <blockquote>In a large, continuing study of upward mobility based at Harvard, commuting time has emerged as the single strongest factor in the odds of escaping poverty. The longer an average commute in a given county, the worse the chances of low-income families there moving up the ladder.</blockquote>

            <blockquote>The relationship between transportation and social mobility is stronger than that between mobility and several other factors, like crime, elementary-school test scores or the percentagjn  of two-parent families in a community, said Nathaniel Hendren, a Harvard economist and one of the researchers on the study.</blockquote>

